    {"id": 20, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "Amendment Process", "question": "An amendment to the Constitution can be proposed by:", "options": ["The president alone", "A simple majority in the House", "The Supreme Court", "A two-thirds vote in both houses of Congress"], "answer": "D", "explanation": "Article V requires a two-thirds vote in both chambers or a constitutional convention called by the states."},
    {"id": 21, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "Federalist No. 10 (Stimulus)", "question": "\"The latent causes of faction are thus sown in the nature of man.\" — James Madison, Federalist No. 10\n\nBased on the quote, Madison believed that factions:", "options": ["Can be eliminated through education", "Should be outlawed by the government", "Only arise in small republics", "Are an inevitable part of human nature"], "answer": "D", "explanation": "Madison acknowledged factions are natural and focused on controlling their effects rather than eliminating them."},
    {"id": 22, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "Federalist No. 51 (Stimulus)", "question": "\"If men were angels, no government would be necessary.\" — James Madison, Federalist No. 51\n\nThis quote supports the argument that:", "options": ["Government must have mechanisms to control itself and those it governs", "Democracy is impossible", "People are inherently good", "The Articles of Confederation were sufficient"], "answer": "A", "explanation": "Madison argued that because people are not perfect, government with checks is essential."},
    {"id": 23, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "Constitutional Principles", "question": "Popular sovereignty means that:", "options": ["The president has supreme authority", "Government power comes from the people", "States are sovereign over the federal government", "Judges make all final decisions"], "answer": "B", "explanation": "Popular sovereignty holds that legitimate government authority derives from the consent of the governed."},
    {"id": 24, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "Three-Fifths Compromise", "question": "The Three-Fifths Compromise addressed the issue of:", "options": ["Presidential elections", "How enslaved people would be counted for representation and taxation", "Judicial appointments", "Freedom of speech"], "answer": "B", "explanation": "Enslaved people were counted as three-fifths of a person for apportionment and taxation."},
    {"id": 25, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "Ratification Debate", "question": "The Federalist Papers were written primarily to:", "options": ["Oppose the Constitution", "Amend the Articles of Confederation", "Establish the Bill of Rights", "Persuade New York to ratify the Constitution"], "answer": "D", "explanation": "Hamilton, Madison, and Jay wrote the Federalist Papers to build support for ratification."},
    {"id": 26, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "Limited Government", "question": "The concept of limited government means that:", "options": ["The government can do anything it wants", "Only the judiciary has limits", "Government power is restricted by law", "States have no power"], "answer": "C", "explanation": "Limited government means officials must operate within constitutional constraints."},
    {"id": 27, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "Natural Rights", "question": "According to John Locke, if a government violates the social contract, people have the right to:", "options": ["Obey without question", "Alter or abolish the government", "Appeal to a foreign power", "Ignore all laws permanently"], "answer": "B", "explanation": "Locke argued the people can replace a government that fails to protect their rights."},
    {"id": 28, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "Participatory Democracy", "question": "Participatory democracy emphasizes:", "options": ["Broad citizen involvement in politics", "Elite decision-making", "Military rule", "Judicial supremacy"], "answer": "A", "explanation": "Participatory democracy values direct citizen engagement in political processes."},
    {"id": 29, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "Pluralist Democracy", "question": "A pluralist model of democracy holds that:", "options": ["One elite group controls policy", "Power is spread among many competing groups", "Only wealthy people have influence", "The president decides everything"], "answer": "B", "explanation": "Pluralism asserts that policy emerges from competition among diverse interest groups."},
    {"id": 30, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "Elite Democracy", "question": "The elitist theory of democracy argues that:", "options": ["All citizens have equal power", "Interest groups don't matter", "Congress represents everyone equally", "A small number of wealthy and powerful individuals dominate politics"], "answer": "D", "explanation": "Elite theory holds that a small, powerful group disproportionately influences government."},
    {"id": 31, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "Marbury v. Madison", "question": "Marbury v. Madison (1803) established the principle of:", "options": ["Executive privilege", "Judicial review", "Federalism", "Popular sovereignty"], "answer": "B", "explanation": "Chief Justice Marshall's ruling established the Supreme Court's power to strike down unconstitutional laws."},
    {"id": 32, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "McCulloch v. Maryland", "question": "In McCulloch v. Maryland (1819), the Supreme Court ruled that:", "options": ["The president can dissolve Congress", "The Bill of Rights does not apply to states", "States cannot tax federal institutions", "Congress cannot establish a national bank"], "answer": "C", "explanation": "The Court upheld the national bank and ruled states cannot tax the federal government."},
    {"id": 33, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "United States v. Lopez", "question": "In United States v. Lopez (1995), the Supreme Court limited:", "options": ["The president's executive power", "The states' power to regulate education", "The judiciary's power of review", "Congress's use of the Commerce Clause"], "answer": "D", "explanation": "The Court ruled that carrying a gun near a school was not economic activity under the Commerce Clause."},
    {"id": 34, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "Implied Powers", "question": "Implied powers of Congress are those that are:", "options": ["Explicitly listed in Article I", "Not in the Constitution but necessary to carry out enumerated powers", "Reserved to the states", "Granted by the president"], "answer": "B", "explanation": "Implied powers derive from the Necessary and Proper Clause."},
    {"id": 35, "unit": "Unit 1", "unitName": "Foundations of American Democracy", "concept": "Cooperative Federalism", "question": "Cooperative federalism is best described as:", "options": ["States acting completely independently", "The federal government controlling everything", "Federal and state governments sharing responsibilities on policy issues", "States ignoring federal mandates"], "answer": "C", "explanation": "Cooperative federalism involves intergovernmental collaboration on programs."},
